Perfect — let me show you a **cleaned-up version of the actual `jQuery.parseHTML` function** so you can see exactly what the meaningful lines look like, without all the archive noise:

```js
// Simplified version of jQuery.parseHTML
jQuery.parseHTML = function( data, context, keepScripts ) {
    if ( !data || typeof data !== "string" ) {
        return null;
    }

    // If context is a boolean, treat it as keepScripts
    if ( typeof context === "boolean" ) {
        keepScripts = context;
        context = false;
    }

    // Default to the current document
    context = context || document;

    var parsed = rsingleTag.exec( data ),
        scripts = !keepScripts && [];

    // Handle single tags like "<div>"
    if ( parsed ) {
        return [ context.createElement( parsed[1] ) ];
    }

    // Build a fragment for more complex HTML
    parsed = buildFragment( [ data ], context, scripts );

    // Remove scripts if keepScripts is false
    if ( scripts && scripts.length ) {
        jQuery( scripts ).remove();
    }

    return jQuery.merge( [], parsed.childNodes );
};
```

---

### 🔎 What Each Part Does
- **Input check** → returns `null` if the input isn’t a string.  
- **Context setup** → decides whether to keep scripts and which document to use.  
- **Single tag optimization** → quickly creates elements like `<p>` or `<div>`.  
- **Fragment building** → parses complex HTML into DOM nodes.  
- **Script removal** → strips `<script>` tags unless explicitly allowed.  
- **Return value** → gives back an array of DOM nodes ready to be inserted into the page.

