Perfect. Here’s your **Chrome Extension Audit Script**—quick, clean, and ready to paste into PowerShell. It will:

- List each extension’s ID
- Extract its name and permissions from `manifest.json`
- Flag any with **broad or dangerous permissions**

---

### 🧪 PowerShell: Chrome Extension Audit

```powershell
# === Chrome Extension Audit ===

$extPath = "$env:LOCALAPPDATA\Google\Chrome\User Data\Default\Extensions"

if (Test-Path $extPath) {
    Get-ChildItem $extPath | ForEach-Object {
        $id = $_.Name
        $manifest = "$($_.FullName)\manifest.json"
        if (Test-Path $manifest) {
            try {
                $json = Get-Content $manifest -Raw | ConvertFrom-Json
                $name = $json.name
                $perms = $json.permissions -join ", "
                Write-Host "`n🧩 Extension ID: $id"
                Write-Host "Name: $name"
                Write-Host "Permissions: $perms"

                if ($perms -match "tabs|history|webRequest|webNavigation|*://*/*|<all_urls>") {
                    Write-Host "⚠️  Suspicious permissions detected!" -ForegroundColor Yellow
                }
            } catch {
                Write-Host "❌ Failed to parse: $id"
            }
        } else {
            Write-Host "❌ No manifest found for: $id"
        }
    }
} else {
    Write-Host "❌ Chrome extensions folder not found."
}
```

---

## 🧭 What to Look For

- **Permissions like**:
  - `tabs`, `history`, `webRequest`, `webNavigation`
  - `*://*/*` or `<all_urls>`
- These can allow:
  - Full access to your browsing history
  - Interception of web traffic
  - Credential harvesting or data exfiltration

